utterances.speaker: A
utterances.text: Okay, understood.

utterances.speaker: B
utterances.text: No, I know what you're after, to be honest. I stepped away and stepped away.

utterances.speaker: A
utterances.text: I understand. But I did want to ask you, because you mentioned AI a couple of times, where do you think we are in terms of the evolution of deploying AI in radiation oncology and how do you think AI application will evolve in the coming years in this space?

utterances.speaker: B
utterances.text: Oh, boy. So my general statement about AI is there only as good as the person who programs them. And when I left, most of the AI systems that I was personally using were effective in what they could do and were very ineffective in things that they were not designed to do, but I wanted them to do. For example, worrying about normal tissue exposure, dealing with brain tissue landscape was very difficult. And in working on validating new AI systems, the reliance on training data sets, I know this is probably more weeds than what you want, but I noticed that many of the AI systems were developed on a specific group of patients, and they were reiterated on those same patients, and then those same patients were what was publicized as their accuracy rate. And as soon as you took that AI into virgin patients that had not been part of the training set, which was also the validation set, you saw a decrease in their ability to work to the point that I had to abandon an AI metric. So I think if anything in the landscape that needs to be done is an agreement on the testing protocols of how new AI gets developed. They had begun talking about them when I had left the department six or seven years ago, but I don't know where they are currently. There's a big ego gets involved to a certain degree, and so it becomes difficult to question that. I think Nah had started to question more of those protocols, but when you have development within companies, it's hard to understand that where that protocol is influencing the AI that a company uses. I think if companies are not testing their AI development on novel cases and rating accuracy from that perspective, they're doing a disservice to their potential customers that there's going to be a lot of frustration on the customer end of applying that AI technology and probably will prevent it from being implemented.

utterances.speaker: A
utterances.text: Okay. Did you feel, from your perspective that either Variant or Aleca had a significant leg up in terms of development of AI capabilities?

utterances.speaker: B
utterances.text: Since we only use the one system for our animal therapies, I don't think I could accurately give a comparison. Okay.

utterances.speaker: A
utterances.text: No, that's totally fine. All right, good. Well, I think we've gotten through our questions, and that's a good spot for us to wrap up. So I really appreciate your time, and thanks a lot for your perspective on this, and have a great rest of the day.

utterances.speaker: B
utterances.text: All right, take care.

utterances.speaker: A
utterances.text: Thank you. All right, bye.
